docs.lead_paragraph: Diamonds, among the hardest materials in the world, are formed from millions of years of geological pressure and must be extracted from mines deep in the earth. But stones with the same chemical properties as diamonds can now be made in laboratories. There are two methods of growing synthetic diamonds, and the process can be completed in as little as two weeks. Both options require a diamond seed — a single crystal diamond — from which a larger stone can form.

headline.main: How to Make a Synthetic Diamond
headline.print_headline: How to Make a Synthetic Diamond

docs.abstract: De Beers is getting into the lab-created diamond business with a new line of fashion jewelry and an aggressive pricing strategy.
docs.snippet: De Beers is getting into the lab-created diamond business with a new line of fashion jewelry and an aggressive pricing strategy.
docs.lead_paragraph: OXFORDSHIRE, England — In a white industrial building in the rolling hills of the English countryside 16 miles from Oxford, silver machines shaped like spaceships hum inside vast laboratories. They are replicating the extreme pressure and temperatures found deep in the earth’s crust and producing, in mere weeks, what historically nature managed only over billions of years: flawless diamonds.

headline.main: ‘Diamonds Are Forever,’ and Made by Machine
headline.print_headline: ‘Diamonds Are Forever,’ And Made By Machine
